1
00:00:01,361 --> 00:00:03,361
(WIND HOWLING)

2
00:00:12,641 --> 00:00:13,641
Ah!

3
00:00:17,921 --> 00:00:19,161
(EXCLAIMS)

4
00:00:19,241 --> 00:00:20,721
(PANTING)

5
00:00:28,321 --> 00:00:29,601
(GRUNTING)

6
00:00:36,841 --> 00:00:38,761
(BREATHING HEAVILY)

7
00:00:38,841 --> 00:00:39,841
No.

8
00:00:42,521 --> 00:00:44,641
(SCREAMING) No!

9
00:00:48,201 --> 00:00:50,201
(THEME MUSIC PLAYING)

10
00:01:23,881 --> 00:01:25,481
(ENGINE HUMMING)

11
00:02:34,601 --> 00:02:36,361
(TARDIS WHOOSHING)

12
00:02:42,601 --> 00:02:43,881
Hello.

13
00:02:44,481 --> 00:02:45,721
I'm Doctor Who.

14
00:02:48,481 --> 00:02:51,161
And these are my plucky assistants.

15
00:02:51,401 --> 00:02:53,961
Thing One and the Other One.

16
00:02:54,041 --> 00:02:55,201
Bill, Nardole.

17
00:02:55,561 --> 00:02:57,521
We picked up your distress call

18
00:02:58,401 --> 00:03:01,361
and here we are to help,
like awesome heroes.

19
00:03:02,441 --> 00:03:03,561
Yeah, we're not assistants. That's...

20
00:03:03,641 --> 00:03:05,961
Okay, right.
So what does he call you? Companions?

21
00:03:06,041 --> 00:03:07,281
Pets?

22
00:03:07,361 --> 00:03:09,641
-Snacks?
-(ALARM BLARING)

23
00:03:09,961 --> 00:03:11,001
Oh!

24
00:03:11,761 --> 00:03:12,841
Someone's watching!

25
00:03:14,481 --> 00:03:15,521
Well, it's

26
00:03:16,241 --> 00:03:17,641
quite a good beat, really, isn't it?

27
00:03:17,721 --> 00:03:19,401
Yeah. Maybe we should be moving on?

28
00:03:19,481 --> 00:03:20,561
Yeah. And he calls us friends.

29
00:03:20,641 --> 00:03:23,561
Ew, Doctor! Think of the age gap!

30
00:03:23,641 --> 00:03:25,441
DOCTOR: (OVER RADIO)
Stop mucking about and concentrate.

31
00:03:25,521 --> 00:03:27,601
Nardole, do something non-irritating.

32
00:03:27,681 --> 00:03:28,681
NARDOLE: On it sir.

33
00:03:28,761 --> 00:03:31,161
MISSY: Time Lords
are friends with each other, dear.

34
00:03:31,241 --> 00:03:33,001
Everything else is cradle-snatching.

35
00:03:33,081 --> 00:03:34,561
NARDOLE: Oh, it's a big one.

36
00:03:34,641 --> 00:03:38,641
Ship reads as 400 miles long
and 100 miles wide.

37
00:03:38,721 --> 00:03:40,521
It's big. Even for a colony ship.

38
00:03:40,601 --> 00:03:41,801
Anything else?

39
00:03:41,881 --> 00:03:42,881
Uh...

40
00:03:43,721 --> 00:03:44,721
Hmm!

41
00:03:47,641 --> 00:03:48,881
Ooh, look at that.

42
00:03:48,961 --> 00:03:52,281
Finally. It's like watching plants grow.

43
00:03:53,041 --> 00:03:54,561
It's heading towards a black hole!

44
00:03:54,641 --> 00:03:56,201
-No.
-No, it isn't!

45
00:03:56,281 --> 00:03:58,841
It was heading towards a black hole
until somebody noticed.

46
00:03:59,481 --> 00:04:01,481
MISSY: Now they're trying
to reverse away from it.

47
00:04:01,561 --> 00:04:04,081
Engines are on reverse thrust, see?

48
00:04:04,161 --> 00:04:05,521
NARDOLE: Hmm.

49
00:04:05,601 --> 00:04:06,961
Well, it's succeeding.

50
00:04:07,041 --> 00:04:09,241
Very, very slowly.

51
00:04:09,561 --> 00:04:11,081
It explains the distress call, I guess.

52
00:04:11,681 --> 00:04:14,241
So. A 400-mile ship

53
00:04:14,321 --> 00:04:17,521
reversing away
from the gravitational pull

54
00:04:18,201 --> 00:04:19,281
of a black hole.

55
00:04:20,201 --> 00:04:21,401
Are we having fun yet?

56
00:04:21,481 --> 00:04:22,641
Mmm.

57
00:04:23,361 --> 00:04:24,761
-(STATIC CRACKLING)
-Hello?

58
00:04:25,121 --> 00:04:26,121
MAN: Who's there?

59
00:04:26,641 --> 00:04:28,321
Hello? Please report status.

60
00:04:28,401 --> 00:04:30,281
Oh! Hello.

61
00:04:30,361 --> 00:04:35,321
What have we got here?
You're probably handsome, aren't you?

62
00:04:35,401 --> 00:04:37,961
Well, congratulations
on your relative symmetry.

63
00:04:38,041 --> 00:04:39,041
Who are you?

64
00:04:39,401 --> 00:04:43,921
Well, I am that mysterious adventurer
in all of time and space

65
00:04:44,001 --> 00:04:46,841
known only as Doctor Who.

66
00:04:46,921 --> 00:04:49,041
And these are my disposables.

67
00:04:49,121 --> 00:04:51,961
Exposition and Comic Relief.

68
00:04:52,041 --> 00:04:53,641
We're not functions!

69
00:04:53,721 --> 00:04:54,921
Darling, those were genders.

70
00:04:55,641 --> 00:04:58,241
Please, stay exactly where you are
for your own safety.

71
00:04:58,321 --> 00:05:00,361
He likes me! So exciting.

72
00:05:00,441 --> 00:05:01,641
-I'm coming through.
-(STATIC CRACKLING)

73
00:05:02,401 --> 00:05:04,241
Hurry, my stallion!

74
00:05:04,321 --> 00:05:07,361
And if I'm in the shower,
just bring me some beans on toast!

75
00:05:07,441 --> 00:05:08,521
-That's...
-Ugh.

76
00:05:09,121 --> 00:05:10,441
That's roughly human flirting, isn't it?

77
00:05:10,521 --> 00:05:13,161
So, why do you keep calling yourself
Doctor Who?

78
00:05:13,241 --> 00:05:16,801
Because I'm pretending to be him,
because that's the whole point

79
00:05:16,881 --> 00:05:19,241
of this ridiculous exercise.

80
00:05:19,321 --> 00:05:21,561
It's not an exercise, it's a test.

81
00:05:22,681 --> 00:05:23,721
Are you eating?

82
00:05:24,361 --> 00:05:26,441
-No.
-MISSY: Yeah, well, don't test me

83
00:05:26,521 --> 00:05:27,921
eating crisps!

84
00:05:28,001 --> 00:05:30,961
Yeah, but he's called
"The Doctor", so...

85
00:05:31,041 --> 00:05:34,241
But he says, "I'm the Doctor”,
and they say, "Doctor Who?"

86
00:05:34,321 --> 00:05:36,001
See, I'm cutting to the chase, baby.

87
00:05:36,081 --> 00:05:37,321
I'm streamlining.

88
00:05:37,401 --> 00:05:39,961
-(SNAPPING FINGERS)
-I'm saving us actual minutes.

89
00:05:40,761 --> 00:05:42,281
Yeah, okay, whatever. (SCOFFS)

90
00:05:42,361 --> 00:05:44,441
-Also, it's his real name.
-It's what?

91
00:05:45,081 --> 00:05:46,281
Look at the screens.

92
00:05:46,641 --> 00:05:47,961
Slow today, Missy.

93
00:05:48,041 --> 00:05:50,521
MISSY: All those screens have been
angled to a single view-point.

94
00:05:50,601 --> 00:05:52,681
But not originally.
They've all been moved.

95
00:05:52,761 --> 00:05:55,001
-Which means?
-Giant ship, single pilot.

96
00:05:55,081 --> 00:05:56,201
But not designed that way.

97
00:05:56,281 --> 00:05:57,681
Something's happened to the others.

98
00:05:57,761 --> 00:06:02,241
Yes! And now it's time for you
to figure out what.

99
00:06:06,321 --> 00:06:08,561
Uh-oh! Someone else has noticed us.

100
00:06:08,641 --> 00:06:10,921
Sorry. What do you mean,
it's his real name?

101
00:06:11,001 --> 00:06:12,481
Nobody knows the Doctor's real name.

102
00:06:12,761 --> 00:06:14,881
I do. Because I grew up with him.

103
00:06:15,281 --> 00:06:17,241
And his real name is Doctor Who!

104
00:06:18,441 --> 00:06:20,481
Bill, she's just trying to wind you up.

105
00:06:20,921 --> 00:06:23,761
He chose it himself. You know,
trying to sound mysterious.

106
00:06:23,841 --> 00:06:25,441
And then he dropped the Who
when he realised

107
00:06:25,521 --> 00:06:27,601
it was a tiny bit on the nose.

108
00:06:27,681 --> 00:06:29,201
Stop teasing her and focus.

109
00:06:29,281 --> 00:06:32,641
Is she serious, though, Doctor?
Is your real name Doctor Who?

110
00:06:35,961 --> 00:06:38,001
Oh, you're blue! Nice.

111
00:06:38,401 --> 00:06:39,721
I should go back to blue.

112
00:06:40,881 --> 00:06:42,041
Stay where you are!

113
00:06:42,321 --> 00:06:44,441
DOCTOR:
Stay calm! He's very frightened.

114
00:06:44,921 --> 00:06:46,681
Dearie me, I thought you were handsome!

115
00:06:46,761 --> 00:06:49,561
Now you've gone all cross
and you're pointing a gun at me.

116
00:06:50,041 --> 00:06:53,281
Is this the emotion
you humans call spanking?

117
00:06:53,601 --> 00:06:54,601
Are there only three of you?

118
00:06:54,681 --> 00:06:56,761
-Are any of you human?
-MISSY: What has happened to this ship

119
00:06:56,841 --> 00:06:59,721
and how long have you been here alone?
You're looking very sickly.

120
00:07:00,041 --> 00:07:01,881
Two days. Are you human?

121
00:07:01,961 --> 00:07:03,921
-Oh, don't be a bitch.
-How did you get on board?

122
00:07:04,521 --> 00:07:05,921
-MAN: Is that your capsule?
-Yep!

123
00:07:06,001 --> 00:07:07,841
-No!
-There. Look!

124
00:07:11,281 --> 00:07:13,081
MAN: Three lifts. They're coming!

125
00:07:14,321 --> 00:07:15,601
What's in this ship?

126
00:07:15,681 --> 00:07:17,521
Super-fast inertia lifts.

127
00:07:17,961 --> 00:07:19,841
Well, what's inside?
What's coming up here?

128
00:07:19,921 --> 00:07:23,001
Things! Uh...
I don't even know where they came from.

129
00:07:23,081 --> 00:07:24,121
One of you must be human.

130
00:07:24,201 --> 00:07:25,921
They only come up
if they detect human life signs!

131
00:07:26,001 --> 00:07:27,641
-What for?
-MAN: They take them away.

132
00:07:28,161 --> 00:07:30,921
So those are the lift doors, yeah?
That's where they come out?

133
00:07:31,001 --> 00:07:32,041
I'll be right with you.

134
00:07:32,481 --> 00:07:33,681
Which of you is human?

135
00:07:37,121 --> 00:07:39,521
Me! (STAMMERING) Me, I'm human.

136
00:07:40,081 --> 00:07:42,081
I'm the only one. Just... Just me.

137
00:07:43,401 --> 00:07:44,441
Please, stop this.

138
00:07:45,481 --> 00:07:47,081
Stop right there. Now.

139
00:07:47,161 --> 00:07:48,961
I'm sorry. I'm so sorry,

140
00:07:49,041 --> 00:07:50,601
but you're the reason
that they're coming.

141
00:07:51,281 --> 00:07:52,761
Put it down. Put that down now.

142
00:07:52,841 --> 00:07:54,241
They won't come if she's dead.

143
00:07:54,321 --> 00:07:55,401
You don't need to do this.

144
00:07:55,801 --> 00:07:58,681
I can get her off the ship.
I can shield her life signs.

145
00:07:58,761 --> 00:07:59,921
You know what, Doctor?

146
00:08:01,081 --> 00:08:02,441
I said this was a bad idea.

147
00:08:02,881 --> 00:08:04,801
Please, listen to me. Look at me!

148
00:08:05,921 --> 00:08:07,401
DOCTOR: Come on, look at me!

149
00:08:08,041 --> 00:08:09,081
That's good.

150
00:08:10,561 --> 00:08:11,841
That's very, very good.

151
00:08:13,161 --> 00:08:16,681
Now, do you see this madwoman
sitting in this chair?

152
00:08:16,761 --> 00:08:18,401
-Her name isn't Doctor Who.
-(SMACKS LIPS)

153
00:08:19,121 --> 00:08:20,641
My name is Doctor Who.

154
00:08:21,041 --> 00:08:23,041
-It's not, is it?
-I like it.

155
00:08:23,761 --> 00:08:25,921
You don't know it yet,
but in a short time,

156
00:08:26,001 --> 00:08:28,041
you will trust me with your life.

157
00:08:28,321 --> 00:08:30,481
And when I save you
and everyone on your ship,

158
00:08:31,201 --> 00:08:34,441
one day you will look back
and wonder who I was,

159
00:08:34,841 --> 00:08:36,281
-or why I...
-(GRUNTS)

160
00:08:47,841 --> 00:08:49,201
(SIZZLING)

161
00:08:50,721 --> 00:08:51,721
(GRUNTING)

162
00:09:00,161 --> 00:09:02,841
BILL: Doctor, this is a bad idea.
DOCTOR: No, it's a good idea.

163
00:09:02,921 --> 00:09:06,401
A test run. She thinks she could be me.
Let's try her out.

164
00:09:06,481 --> 00:09:08,881
-Why?
-She got us home from Mars.

165
00:09:08,961 --> 00:09:10,161
She's a murderer!

166
00:09:11,841 --> 00:09:13,681
Enjoying your bacon sandwich?

167
00:09:14,321 --> 00:09:17,121
-Why?
-Because it had a mummy and a daddy.

168
00:09:17,681 --> 00:09:19,961
Go tell a pig
about your moral high ground.

169
00:09:20,201 --> 00:09:22,361
I pick a scenario,
we drop her down into it,

170
00:09:22,441 --> 00:09:23,481
and we see how she does.

171
00:09:25,841 --> 00:09:26,841
How does that work?

172
00:09:26,921 --> 00:09:29,721
Ah. We're just
take the TARDIS for a spin,

173
00:09:29,801 --> 00:09:32,321
and we graze for distress calls.

174
00:09:33,001 --> 00:09:35,561
We'll pick a good one.
Our usual Saturday.

175
00:09:36,321 --> 00:09:38,841
And, uh... What if she just walks out

176
00:09:38,921 --> 00:09:40,681
and slaughters everyone,
just for a laugh?

177
00:09:40,761 --> 00:09:43,521
Well, I will be monitoring you
the whole time.

178
00:09:44,281 --> 00:09:45,841
-Me?
-Yes.

179
00:09:45,921 --> 00:09:49,321
You and Nardole.
You can be her companions. Hey!

180
00:09:49,961 --> 00:09:51,921
(LAUGHING) Nah, forget it.

181
00:09:52,001 --> 00:09:53,001
Absolutely no way.

182
00:09:53,961 --> 00:09:55,001
Nardole agreed.

183
00:09:55,481 --> 00:09:56,521
No, I didn't!

184
00:09:56,601 --> 00:09:58,441
You did in my head,
which is good enough for me.

185
00:09:58,521 --> 00:09:59,841
Why do you want to do this?

186
00:10:00,641 --> 00:10:03,081
She's my friend!
She's my oldest friend in the Universe.

187
00:10:03,361 --> 00:10:05,321
Well, you've got lots of friends!
Better ones.

188
00:10:05,401 --> 00:10:07,361
-What's so special about her?
-She's different.

189
00:10:07,441 --> 00:10:08,601
Different how?

190
00:10:09,721 --> 00:10:10,961
I don't know.

191
00:10:15,441 --> 00:10:16,441
Yes, you do.

192
00:10:21,641 --> 00:10:25,241
She's the only person I've ever met
who's even remotely like me.

193
00:10:27,561 --> 00:10:28,601
Uh...

194
00:10:29,041 --> 00:10:31,881
So, more than anything,
you want her to be good?

195
00:10:41,401 --> 00:10:43,001
Are you having an emotion?

196
00:10:45,121 --> 00:10:46,481
I know I can help her.

197
00:10:46,561 --> 00:10:49,521
Yeah! Look at that face.
He's having an emotion.

198
00:10:49,601 --> 00:10:52,041
Yeah. Yes, look at that bit.
Yeah, he's doing emotion.

199
00:10:52,121 --> 00:10:54,761
-Oh, leave him alone.
-Can I take a selfie with you?

200
00:10:57,041 --> 00:10:58,961
-(SHUTTER CLICKS)
-DOCTOR: She was my first friend.

201
00:10:59,041 --> 00:11:02,441
Always so brilliant.
From the first day at the Academy.

202
00:11:03,921 --> 00:11:05,201
So fast. So funny!

203
00:11:05,641 --> 00:11:07,961
-She was my man-crush.
-What, I'm sorry?

204
00:11:08,641 --> 00:11:09,641
Yeah.

205
00:11:10,161 --> 00:11:12,921
I think she was a man back then.
I'm fairly sure that I was, too.

206
00:11:13,001 --> 00:11:14,601
It was a long time ago, though.

207
00:11:15,321 --> 00:11:17,561
So, Time Lords...

208
00:11:18,361 --> 00:11:20,921
A bit flexible on the whole
man-woman thing then, yeah?

209
00:11:21,601 --> 00:11:23,721
We're the most civilised civilisation
in the Universe.

210
00:11:23,801 --> 00:11:27,961
We're billions of years beyond
your petty human obsession with gender

211
00:11:28,041 --> 00:11:29,721
and its associated stereotypes.

212
00:11:30,361 --> 00:11:33,401
But you still
call yourselves Time "Lords"?

213
00:11:34,761 --> 00:11:36,241
-Yeah, shut up.
-(CHUCKLES)

214
00:11:36,641 --> 00:11:37,641
Okay.

215
00:11:39,681 --> 00:11:42,361
We had a pact, me and him.

216
00:11:43,881 --> 00:11:48,641
Every star in the Universe,
we were going to see them all.

217
00:11:50,601 --> 00:11:52,601
But he was too busy burning them.

218
00:11:53,921 --> 00:11:55,681
I don't think she ever saw anything.

219
00:11:56,761 --> 00:11:59,161
And you think that if she did,
she'd change?

220
00:12:01,721 --> 00:12:02,721
I know she would.

221
00:12:03,321 --> 00:12:04,321
I know it.

222
00:12:07,281 --> 00:12:10,361
(SCOFFS) You're a bloody idiot,
you know that, yeah?

223
00:12:11,361 --> 00:12:12,361
Of course.

224
00:12:18,201 --> 00:12:19,441
She scares me.

225
00:12:24,521 --> 00:12:27,121
Like, she really scares me.

226
00:12:33,681 --> 00:12:36,201
Okay. So promise me one thing.

227
00:12:36,281 --> 00:12:37,281
Yeah?

228
00:12:38,201 --> 00:12:39,921
Just promise you won't get me killed.

229
00:12:40,681 --> 00:12:41,801
(BREATHING SHAKILY)

230
00:12:44,081 --> 00:12:45,081
I'm sorry.

231
00:12:47,481 --> 00:12:50,761
-I can't promise you that!
-(CHUCKLING) Thanks.

232
00:12:53,681 --> 00:12:54,921
I mean, look.

233
00:12:55,521 --> 00:12:56,681
You're human!

234
00:12:57,601 --> 00:12:59,961
-And humans are so mortal.
-Cheers!

235
00:13:00,281 --> 00:13:01,841
I mean, you pop like balloons.

236
00:13:08,481 --> 00:13:10,441
I mean, one heart?

237
00:13:11,561 --> 00:13:13,801
It's your most important organ
and you have no back-up!

238
00:13:13,881 --> 00:13:15,001
It's like a budget cut.

239
00:13:15,961 --> 00:13:18,001
Or you could try and keep me alive.

240
00:13:20,041 --> 00:13:21,601
DOCTOR: Within reason.

241
00:13:21,681 --> 00:13:22,961
BILL: Thanks, mate.

242
00:13:25,681 --> 00:13:27,241
-(LIFT BELL DINGS)
-(DOOR OPENING)

243
00:13:32,961 --> 00:13:34,041
What are they?

244
00:13:35,401 --> 00:13:37,081
NARDOLE: What are those things?

245
00:13:39,441 --> 00:13:41,081
You're too late. She's dead.

246
00:13:42,201 --> 00:13:44,121
Don't you touch her.
Don't you lay a finger on her.

247
00:13:44,201 --> 00:13:48,801
AUTOMATED VOICE:
Stand. Away. Stand. Away.

248
00:13:48,881 --> 00:13:52,281
She will be repaired.

249
00:13:52,361 --> 00:13:55,081
-Repaired?
-Stand. Away.

250
00:13:55,161 --> 00:13:56,441
You can help her, is that what you mean?

251
00:14:01,281 --> 00:14:02,641
Where are you going?
What are you gonna do with her?

252
00:14:02,721 --> 00:14:03,921
Repair.

253
00:14:04,001 --> 00:14:05,721
Don't try to stop them.
They'll snap you in half.

254
00:14:05,801 --> 00:14:07,161
When do you bring her back?

255
00:14:07,241 --> 00:14:09,521
We will not.

256
00:14:14,521 --> 00:14:15,641
Wait for me.

257
00:14:16,681 --> 00:14:17,681
Wait for me.

258
00:14:17,761 --> 00:14:18,881
DOCTOR: (ECHOING) Wait for me.

259
00:14:18,961 --> 00:14:21,961
-What are you doing?
-Leaving a message in her subconscious.

260
00:14:22,041 --> 00:14:23,121
How? She's dead.

261
00:14:23,201 --> 00:14:25,361
Those things are going to repair her,
so clearly, she isn't.

262
00:14:25,441 --> 00:14:26,841
-Assumption.
-Deduction.

263
00:14:26,921 --> 00:14:27,921
-Hope.
-Faith.

264
00:14:28,001 --> 00:14:29,041
-Idiot.
-Always.

265
00:14:29,121 --> 00:14:30,881
Sir, step away from those doors.
You'll bring them back.

266
00:14:30,961 --> 00:14:32,041
What do you care, Smurf?

267
00:14:32,121 --> 00:14:33,801
They're not even interested in you.

268
00:14:33,881 --> 00:14:35,521
Sir, I swear to you.

269
00:14:35,601 --> 00:14:37,441
Step away from that lift
or I will kill you.

270
00:14:37,521 --> 00:14:38,921
Don't. You will only make me angry.

271
00:14:39,001 --> 00:14:40,721
-Honey, listen to him.
-Why?

272
00:14:40,801 --> 00:14:42,081
Because if somebody kills you
and it's not me,

273
00:14:42,161 --> 00:14:43,321
we'll both be disappointed.

274
00:14:43,401 --> 00:14:46,041
Now, you! What were those things?

275
00:14:46,121 --> 00:14:47,201
I don't know.

276
00:14:47,281 --> 00:14:48,641
How can you not know?
They're on your ship.

277
00:14:48,721 --> 00:14:50,121
MAN: The ship is supposed to be empty.

278
00:14:50,201 --> 00:14:52,481
-But it's a colony ship.
-Because it's brand-new.

279
00:14:52,561 --> 00:14:54,241
The colonies haven't arrived yet.

280
00:14:54,321 --> 00:14:55,481
MAN: We were on our way to pick them up.

281
00:14:55,561 --> 00:14:57,201
A skeleton crew.
Fifty of us, that's all.

282
00:14:57,281 --> 00:15:00,081
-(MACHINE BEEPING)
-Well, it's not empty now, is it? Look!

283
00:15:00,481 --> 00:15:01,961
Thousands of life readings.

284
00:15:02,041 --> 00:15:04,601
Two days ago, there was nothing.
Those readings came out of nowhere.

285
00:15:04,681 --> 00:15:06,481
-Well, obviously you were boarded.
-No!

286
00:15:06,561 --> 00:15:08,481
MISSY: Your ship was taken over.
It happens.

287
00:15:08,561 --> 00:15:10,721
-DOCTOR: No.
-Doctor?

288
00:15:10,801 --> 00:15:13,361
This is worse than I thought.
Much worse.

289
00:15:14,761 --> 00:15:17,921
Fifty of you taking your brand new ship,
fresh from the factory,

290
00:15:18,001 --> 00:15:19,561
to pick up some colonists?

291
00:15:19,641 --> 00:15:21,161
-Yes.
-Two days ago,

292
00:15:21,241 --> 00:15:22,561
you almost bump into a black hole.

293
00:15:23,121 --> 00:15:24,121
What did you do then?

294
00:15:24,201 --> 00:15:25,601
We tried to reverse out of it.

295
00:15:26,241 --> 00:15:29,641
And you sent a team down
to the other end of the ship

296
00:15:29,721 --> 00:15:31,321
to reverse the rear thrusters, yes?

297
00:15:31,401 --> 00:15:33,361
-MAN: Yes.
-How many people in the team?

298
00:15:33,441 --> 00:15:34,481
About 20.

299
00:15:34,561 --> 00:15:36,001
And you never heard from them again.

300
00:15:36,441 --> 00:15:39,681
And then the whole ship just lit up
with all these new life forms, correct?

301
00:15:39,761 --> 00:15:41,841
-Exactly!
-What happened then?

302
00:15:41,921 --> 00:15:44,361
Those creatures arrived.
Took the rest of the humans away.

303
00:15:44,441 --> 00:15:46,001
They weren't interested in me.

304
00:15:46,761 --> 00:15:50,081
I tried to fight them
but they were too strong.

305
00:15:50,161 --> 00:15:52,401
Well, maybe something came out
of the black hole?

306
00:15:52,481 --> 00:15:54,041
Nothing comes out of a black hole.

307
00:15:54,481 --> 00:15:55,761
Nothing boarded this ship.

308
00:15:55,841 --> 00:15:57,881
I'm afraid you will never
see your crew again.

309
00:16:00,441 --> 00:16:03,401
Black hole, 400-mile spaceship...

310
00:16:05,281 --> 00:16:06,801
It's a matter of time.

311
00:16:08,481 --> 00:16:09,481
Pay attention.

312
00:16:12,761 --> 00:16:14,241
(RHYTHMIC BEEPING)

313
00:16:32,081 --> 00:16:33,401
Hello.

314
00:16:33,481 --> 00:16:34,601
Back with us?

315
00:16:37,201 --> 00:16:39,641
-(GRUNTING SOFTLY)
-No, don't try to speak. Just relax.

316
00:16:39,721 --> 00:16:40,801
You'll be fine.

317
00:16:41,801 --> 00:16:43,761
Full conversion wasn't necessary.

318
00:16:44,881 --> 00:16:46,521
Though it will be in time.

319
00:16:48,721 --> 00:16:49,881
Sleep now.

320
00:16:54,161 --> 00:16:55,481
(BEEPING CONTINUES)

321
00:17:09,601 --> 00:17:10,841
(GASPS)

322
00:17:15,241 --> 00:17:18,761
Oh, awake, is it? Awake now. Good.

323
00:17:19,361 --> 00:17:20,361
Settle.

324
00:17:21,321 --> 00:17:22,321
(BILL GRUNTING)

325
00:17:28,761 --> 00:17:29,761
(STRAINING)

326
00:17:32,321 --> 00:17:33,441
(GASPING)

327
00:17:41,081 --> 00:17:42,201
Wait for me.

328
00:17:42,761 --> 00:17:43,921
(GASPING) Doctor!

329
00:17:48,201 --> 00:17:49,641
DISTANT AUTOMATED VOICE: Pain.

330
00:17:50,241 --> 00:17:51,241
Pain.

331
00:17:52,401 --> 00:17:53,841
Pain.

332
00:17:57,921 --> 00:17:58,921
Pain.

333
00:17:59,841 --> 00:18:01,201
Pain.

334
00:18:02,521 --> 00:18:03,521
Pain.

335
00:18:04,001 --> 00:18:05,801
(GRUNTING)

336
00:18:09,481 --> 00:18:10,961
Pain.

337
00:18:11,441 --> 00:18:12,441
Pain.

338
00:18:13,761 --> 00:18:14,761
Pain.

339
00:18:21,801 --> 00:18:23,161
(BEEPING)

340
00:18:26,681 --> 00:18:28,201
(MECHANICAL WHIRRING)

341
00:18:28,281 --> 00:18:29,361
Pain.

342
00:18:30,721 --> 00:18:31,721
Pain.

343
00:18:33,241 --> 00:18:34,241
Pain.

344
00:18:36,201 --> 00:18:37,201
Pain.

345
00:18:38,401 --> 00:18:39,401
Pain.

346
00:18:40,561 --> 00:18:41,681
Pain.

347
00:18:43,961 --> 00:18:45,441
(WHIRRING CONTINUES)

348
00:18:47,481 --> 00:18:48,521
Pain.

349
00:18:49,561 --> 00:18:50,561
Pain.

350
00:18:51,641 --> 00:18:52,641
Pain.

351
00:19:06,881 --> 00:19:07,881
Pain.

352
00:19:08,561 --> 00:19:09,561
Pain.

353
00:19:09,881 --> 00:19:11,361
Pain.

354
00:19:21,161 --> 00:19:22,481
(AUTOMATED VOICE GROWING LOUDER) Pain.

355
00:19:22,561 --> 00:19:24,001
Pain.

356
00:19:24,081 --> 00:19:25,201
Pain.

357
00:19:30,721 --> 00:19:32,121
-(BUTTON CLICKING REPEATEDLY)
-Pain.

358
00:19:32,201 --> 00:19:33,681
Pain.

359
00:19:33,761 --> 00:19:35,161
Pain.

360
00:19:37,281 --> 00:19:38,521
Pain.

361
00:19:39,241 --> 00:19:40,641
Pain.

362
00:19:41,721 --> 00:19:43,041
Pain.

363
00:19:44,361 --> 00:19:45,441
Pain.

364
00:19:47,241 --> 00:19:48,361
Pain.

365
00:19:48,801 --> 00:19:49,801
Pain.

366
00:19:50,241 --> 00:19:51,241
Pain.

367
00:19:57,041 --> 00:19:58,241
(SCREAMING)

368
00:19:59,841 --> 00:20:01,481
WOMAN: Who's making all that noise?

369
00:20:02,761 --> 00:20:04,041
Who is it?

370
00:20:04,881 --> 00:20:06,321
(GRUNTING)

371
00:20:13,001 --> 00:20:14,041
Pain.

372
00:20:14,481 --> 00:20:15,601
Pain.

373
00:20:15,681 --> 00:20:17,601
-All right. What's the matter with you?
-Pain.

374
00:20:18,201 --> 00:20:19,361
-Hmm?
-Pain.

375
00:20:19,441 --> 00:20:21,721
-Making all that fuss.
-Pain.

376
00:20:22,681 --> 00:20:23,681
Pain.

377
00:20:24,321 --> 00:20:25,481
See now...

378
00:20:26,841 --> 00:20:27,841
Pain.

379
00:20:27,921 --> 00:20:29,201
Pain.

380
00:20:29,761 --> 00:20:31,361
-Pain.
-WOMAN: Hmm.

381
00:20:33,401 --> 00:20:35,401
-Huh.
-Pain. Pain.

382
00:20:37,121 --> 00:20:38,721
That's better, isn't it?

383
00:20:39,761 --> 00:20:42,721
All right, then, Mr Razor.
I'll just go do the rounds.

384
00:20:42,801 --> 00:20:45,401
-Now I'm here.
-Rounds. Yes, it is.

385
00:20:45,481 --> 00:20:46,841
Rounds. Good. Yes.

386
00:21:02,081 --> 00:21:03,521
(METAL CLANKING)

387
00:21:25,361 --> 00:21:26,921
-(VOLUME INCREASES)
-Pain.

388
00:21:27,041 --> 00:21:28,361
Pain.

389
00:21:29,281 --> 00:21:30,321
Pain.

390
00:21:31,521 --> 00:21:32,521
Pain.

391
00:21:32,921 --> 00:21:34,201
Sorry, mate.

392
00:21:34,281 --> 00:21:36,681
-Pain.
-I'm really sorry.

393
00:21:49,681 --> 00:21:52,721
AUTOMATED VOICE: (GROWING LOUDER)
Kill me. Kill me.

394
00:21:53,241 --> 00:21:55,081
Kill me.

395
00:21:55,161 --> 00:21:56,721
-Kill me.
-Sorry! Sorry.

396
00:21:56,801 --> 00:21:57,801
Sorry.

397
00:22:02,801 --> 00:22:04,321
WOMAN: This way, Mr Razor!

398
00:22:05,081 --> 00:22:06,321
Look sharp.

399
00:22:16,801 --> 00:22:18,081
(RUSTLING)

400
00:22:27,561 --> 00:22:28,681
(GASPING)

401
00:22:31,881 --> 00:22:33,361
Would you like some tea?

402
00:22:38,601 --> 00:22:40,121
This way. This way!

403
00:22:40,201 --> 00:22:41,201
What about him?

404
00:22:42,721 --> 00:22:44,761
He's all right. They don't feel pain.

405
00:22:44,841 --> 00:22:45,841
I think they do.

406
00:22:46,321 --> 00:22:47,481
Yes, they do.

407
00:22:47,681 --> 00:22:48,961
So why did you say they don't?

408
00:22:49,041 --> 00:22:50,521
It was a clever lie.

409
00:22:50,601 --> 00:22:52,361
But you see straight through me.

410
00:22:53,161 --> 00:22:55,361
Come. Tea! This way.

411
00:22:55,441 --> 00:22:57,081
What are those things?

412
00:22:57,161 --> 00:23:00,281
People, people, people, people, people!
People, they are people.

413
00:23:00,361 --> 00:23:01,521
Then what are you doing to them?

414
00:23:02,281 --> 00:23:03,641
Curing them.

415
00:23:04,561 --> 00:23:05,561
Come on.

416
00:23:09,601 --> 00:23:10,601
Psst!

417
00:23:11,441 --> 00:23:12,441
In here.

418
00:23:34,441 --> 00:23:36,681
You want the good tea, or the bad tea?

419
00:23:37,121 --> 00:23:38,121
What's the difference?

420
00:23:38,561 --> 00:23:40,641
I call one "good”, one "bad".

421
00:23:41,321 --> 00:23:43,881
Ah, I'll take the good one...

422
00:23:43,961 --> 00:23:48,481
Excellent. Positive attitude,
will help with the horror to come.

423
00:23:49,041 --> 00:23:50,041
What horror?

424
00:23:51,601 --> 00:23:52,601
Mainly the tea.

425
00:23:53,001 --> 00:23:54,001
(CHUCKLES)

426
00:23:59,241 --> 00:24:00,681
(TEA POURING)

427
00:24:13,961 --> 00:24:14,961
Where am I?

428
00:24:16,441 --> 00:24:17,441
Hospital.

429
00:24:18,481 --> 00:24:21,321
Uh, yeah, but where?

430
00:24:22,121 --> 00:24:24,001
The ship. You are on the ship.

431
00:24:24,081 --> 00:24:25,881
I was on a ship, yeah, but it...

432
00:24:26,521 --> 00:24:27,521
Wasn't like this.

433
00:24:27,601 --> 00:24:31,201
You were at top of the ship,
and now you are at bottom.

434
00:24:36,921 --> 00:24:37,921
Ship.

435
00:24:38,441 --> 00:24:40,201
Top. Bottom.

436
00:24:40,641 --> 00:24:41,641
See?

437
00:24:41,721 --> 00:24:42,721
Yes.

438
00:24:43,481 --> 00:24:44,721
How did I get here?

439
00:24:44,801 --> 00:24:46,441
You were sick, very sick.

440
00:24:47,881 --> 00:24:50,361
Broken. Heart broken.

441
00:24:51,561 --> 00:24:53,281
New heart, good, is it?

442
00:24:53,361 --> 00:24:55,681
Ah, I haven't dared look yet...

443
00:24:55,761 --> 00:24:57,041
Is good. Is very good.

444
00:24:57,121 --> 00:24:58,161
Shiny.

445
00:24:58,721 --> 00:25:01,081
You can... Carry it off.

446
00:25:01,161 --> 00:25:02,521
Not everybody can.

447
00:25:03,081 --> 00:25:07,161
For some people,
it all goes a bit... You know.

448
00:25:07,361 --> 00:25:08,361
What?

449
00:25:09,761 --> 00:25:11,041
Vending machine.

450
00:25:11,121 --> 00:25:12,641
-(LAUGHS NERVOUSLY)
-(LAUGHS)

451
00:25:13,521 --> 00:25:17,281
Drink it while it is very hot,
the pain will disguise the taste.

452
00:25:18,281 --> 00:25:19,281
Thanks.

453
00:25:21,281 --> 00:25:22,281
How long have I been here?

454
00:25:22,361 --> 00:25:23,961
Oh, weeks.

455
00:25:24,041 --> 00:25:26,001
Many weeks, maybe months.

456
00:25:26,841 --> 00:25:27,881
God.

457
00:25:27,961 --> 00:25:29,641
Is good! You get strong.

458
00:25:29,721 --> 00:25:32,361
Yeah, well, I came here with people,
my friends.

459
00:25:32,441 --> 00:25:34,201
Oh, well...

460
00:25:34,281 --> 00:25:35,721
They don't look so bad.

461
00:25:37,441 --> 00:25:38,761
That's them? That's my friends?

462
00:25:38,841 --> 00:25:40,921
I know, I make picture for you.

463
00:25:42,801 --> 00:25:45,441
-You like?
-Where are they now? Are they okay?

464
00:25:45,521 --> 00:25:47,641
Oh, they're fine, look at them.

465
00:25:47,961 --> 00:25:49,321
Yeah, but are they okay now?

466
00:25:49,801 --> 00:25:51,121
That is now.

467
00:25:51,521 --> 00:25:54,001
Is right now. That is them, is live.

468
00:25:54,081 --> 00:25:56,761
Yeah, but they're...
The picture is frozen.

469
00:25:57,281 --> 00:25:58,281
No.

470
00:25:58,801 --> 00:26:01,281
Yeah, it is.
They're not moving, look at them.

471
00:26:02,601 --> 00:26:05,321
They are at top of ship.

472
00:26:05,681 --> 00:26:07,361
Top of ship very slow.

473
00:26:07,441 --> 00:26:10,721
We are at bottom. Bottom much faster.

474
00:26:11,401 --> 00:26:12,761
Very fast bottom.

475
00:26:14,281 --> 00:26:15,761
(CHUCKLES)

476
00:26:18,481 --> 00:26:19,881
Yeah, I don't understand.

477
00:26:21,441 --> 00:26:22,441
Ah...

478
00:26:23,401 --> 00:26:24,801
So, you don't know.

479
00:26:26,721 --> 00:26:27,721
About what?

480
00:26:30,481 --> 00:26:31,601
Short version.

481
00:26:32,041 --> 00:26:36,761
DOCTOR: Because of the black hole,
time is moving faster

482
00:26:36,841 --> 00:26:39,681
at this end of the ship than the other.

483
00:26:41,081 --> 00:26:42,521
It's all about gravity.

484
00:26:44,841 --> 00:26:45,841
(SIGHS)

485
00:26:47,241 --> 00:26:49,721
Gravity slows down time.

486
00:26:49,801 --> 00:26:51,721
The closer you are
to the source of gravity,

487
00:26:51,801 --> 00:26:55,041
the slower time will move.

488
00:26:55,401 --> 00:26:56,521
If you're standing in your garden

489
00:26:56,601 --> 00:26:58,921
your head is travelling faster
through time than your feet.

490
00:27:01,761 --> 00:27:04,241
Don't they teach you this stuff
at space school?

491
00:27:08,201 --> 00:27:09,281
See, he's raising the eyebrow.

492
00:27:09,961 --> 00:27:11,161
That's his sarcasm face.

493
00:27:11,961 --> 00:27:13,041
He's making a joke.

494
00:27:13,761 --> 00:27:15,921
He's been raising
that eyebrow for a week.

495
00:27:17,481 --> 00:27:18,561
So, when are you gonna tell me?

496
00:27:18,641 --> 00:27:20,961
-Tell you what?
-How I can get back up there.

497
00:27:21,961 --> 00:27:25,161
I already told you,
you can't leave here, I'm sorry.

498
00:27:25,241 --> 00:27:26,841
What are you doing in here?

499
00:27:27,321 --> 00:27:29,201
She works for me now, we agreed.

500
00:27:29,281 --> 00:27:31,361
Everyone here works for me.

501
00:27:31,921 --> 00:27:32,921
There's a floor out there.

502
00:27:33,361 --> 00:27:34,361
Needs cleaning.

503
00:27:35,441 --> 00:27:36,801
Running all the way.

504
00:27:37,761 --> 00:27:39,241
I know you dream of leaving.

505
00:27:39,641 --> 00:27:41,041
No... Me?

506
00:27:41,121 --> 00:27:42,121
Never.

507
00:27:42,761 --> 00:27:44,041
-(METAL CLANKING)
-This is your heart now,

508
00:27:44,521 --> 00:27:45,841
but outside this hospital,

509
00:27:46,361 --> 00:27:47,801
it will stop working.

510
00:27:49,321 --> 00:27:51,921
Well, it's a good thing
you've got all those locks then.

511
00:27:52,001 --> 00:27:53,641
In case I accidentally wander off.

512
00:27:57,121 --> 00:27:59,081
Yeah, better get mopping.

513
00:28:02,561 --> 00:28:03,801
Don't change the channel.

514
00:28:05,641 --> 00:28:09,321
A week raising his eyebrow,
why would I change?

515
00:28:11,001 --> 00:28:15,041
Space school? (CLEARS THROAT)
Um, I'm basically the janitor.

516
00:28:16,161 --> 00:28:18,121
-(MISSY CLEARS THROAT)
-Well, that's a good job.

517
00:28:18,201 --> 00:28:19,961
But you gotta concentrate, Paul.

518
00:28:20,561 --> 00:28:22,121
Now, listen.

519
00:28:24,121 --> 00:28:25,601
BILL: He's gonna do an explanation.

520
00:28:25,681 --> 00:28:27,401
That always takes a while.

521
00:28:28,041 --> 00:28:30,001
The months will fly by.

522
00:28:31,041 --> 00:28:32,561
(LAUGHS)

523
00:28:36,601 --> 00:28:39,121
A black hole isn't just any old gravity.

524
00:28:39,201 --> 00:28:40,641
DOCTOR: It's Superman gravity.

525
00:28:40,721 --> 00:28:44,161
If you really want to slow down time,
park next to one of these guys.

526
00:28:44,241 --> 00:28:45,281
Trouble is...

527
00:28:45,681 --> 00:28:50,921
One end of the ship is closer
to the Superman gravity than the other.

528
00:28:57,121 --> 00:28:59,241
(BEEPING)

529
00:29:02,481 --> 00:29:04,641
-(WIND HOWLING)
-(WINDOW CREAKS OPENS)

530
00:29:24,481 --> 00:29:26,801
(MACHINES BEEPING RAPIDLY)

531
00:29:26,881 --> 00:29:28,121
(GASPS)

532
00:29:32,841 --> 00:29:34,001
(BEEPING STOPS)

533
00:29:35,721 --> 00:29:36,721
(SIGHS)

534
00:29:40,121 --> 00:29:41,561
-(GASPS)
-Wait for me.

535
00:29:43,761 --> 00:29:45,561
(CLOCK TICKING)

536
00:29:47,881 --> 00:29:49,681
How much longer, Doctor?

537
00:29:51,041 --> 00:29:52,601
How many more years?

538
00:29:56,881 --> 00:30:00,241
What about these lifeforms?
What are they? Where did they come from?

539
00:30:00,441 --> 00:30:01,561
MAN: How can there be so many?

540
00:30:01,641 --> 00:30:05,001
Those are the descendants
of your crew mates.

541
00:30:05,601 --> 00:30:08,081
DOCTOR: Two days for you,
generations for them.

542
00:30:08,161 --> 00:30:09,201
-What are these...
-Look!

543
00:30:09,281 --> 00:30:10,281
(EXCLAIMS)

544
00:30:11,001 --> 00:30:12,881
BILL: What kind of treatment is that?

545
00:30:15,241 --> 00:30:16,721
Why won't you ever explain?

546
00:30:17,441 --> 00:30:20,281
I do explain.
They are the special patients.

547
00:30:21,801 --> 00:30:24,361
When do those bag things
come off their heads?

548
00:30:24,441 --> 00:30:25,721
They don't.

549
00:30:25,801 --> 00:30:26,801
They don't?

550
00:30:26,881 --> 00:30:29,641
Conversion is permanent.

551
00:30:31,601 --> 00:30:32,601
Why?

552
00:30:34,161 --> 00:30:35,281
We are dying.

553
00:30:36,201 --> 00:30:39,321
All of us on this ship, dying.

554
00:30:41,001 --> 00:30:42,241
(DOOR OPENING)

555
00:30:52,161 --> 00:30:53,401
They are the cure.

556
00:30:54,161 --> 00:30:55,961
They are the future.

557
00:30:58,041 --> 00:31:00,521
AUTOMATED VOICE: Tie me.

558
00:31:01,721 --> 00:31:04,481
Tie me.

559
00:31:05,401 --> 00:31:07,561
Tie me.

560
00:31:07,841 --> 00:31:10,801
To survive,
they are what we must all become.

561
00:31:10,881 --> 00:31:12,161
I will show you.

562
00:31:13,361 --> 00:31:14,801
-Where are we going?
-Outside.

563
00:31:14,881 --> 00:31:17,241
You always want to go outside,
we go outside.

564
00:31:19,521 --> 00:31:20,881
DOCTOR: Wait for me.

565
00:31:23,841 --> 00:31:24,841
Wait for me.

566
00:31:28,481 --> 00:31:29,481
Psst!

567
00:31:40,761 --> 00:31:42,561
(BABY CRYING)

568
00:31:45,361 --> 00:31:46,801
Everyone looks so sick.

569
00:31:47,681 --> 00:31:49,401
This was a good place once.

570
00:31:49,481 --> 00:31:53,281
Hundreds of years ago,
when the settlers first came here.

571
00:31:53,401 --> 00:31:54,921
But this ship is old.

572
00:31:55,281 --> 00:31:57,641
Everything is dying.

573
00:32:01,001 --> 00:32:02,481
Our world is rust.

574
00:32:02,561 --> 00:32:04,961
Our air is engine fumes.

575
00:32:05,041 --> 00:32:07,881
So, we must evolve to survive.

576
00:32:08,521 --> 00:32:10,721
But, evolution is not fast enough.

577
00:32:12,921 --> 00:32:16,641
The special patients, they are strong.

578
00:32:16,721 --> 00:32:20,361
Soon, we will all be upgraded like them.

579
00:32:20,441 --> 00:32:23,721
-BILL: They're in pain.
-The pain will be cured.

580
00:32:23,801 --> 00:32:25,721
And the exodus will begin.

581
00:32:25,801 --> 00:32:26,801
Exodus?

582
00:32:27,401 --> 00:32:28,801
Operation Exodus.

583
00:32:29,361 --> 00:32:30,681
We will leave this city.

584
00:32:31,241 --> 00:32:35,561
We will climb up, through the ship,
and we will take command.

585
00:32:36,281 --> 00:32:37,961
Well, you could just go up right now.

586
00:32:39,841 --> 00:32:41,041
We have to be strong.

587
00:32:41,721 --> 00:32:42,881
There are lifts.

588
00:32:42,961 --> 00:32:44,321
There are many dangers.

589
00:32:44,881 --> 00:32:47,281
I've been up there.
There's a friend of mine, he could help.

590
00:32:47,361 --> 00:32:49,001
You do not understand

591
00:32:49,801 --> 00:32:50,881
the dangers.

592
00:32:52,001 --> 00:32:57,241
Many years ago, there was
an expedition, to floor 507.

593
00:32:57,321 --> 00:32:59,761
The largest of the solar farms.

594
00:33:01,201 --> 00:33:02,201
And?

595
00:33:04,161 --> 00:33:05,161
Silence.

596
00:33:07,361 --> 00:33:08,441
They never came back.

597
00:33:09,721 --> 00:33:11,201
There is something up there.

598
00:33:11,961 --> 00:33:13,201
And we must be strong.

599
00:33:13,281 --> 00:33:14,321
-(BUZZING)
-(GASPS)

600
00:33:14,401 --> 00:33:16,121
-WOMAN: Return to the hospital.
-I don't...

601
00:33:16,201 --> 00:33:17,521
You see, my dear?

602
00:33:17,601 --> 00:33:20,841
You must be strong,
to leave the hospital.

603
00:33:20,921 --> 00:33:24,081
And you will be. Soon, very soon.

604
00:33:25,041 --> 00:33:27,601
-(BILL GROANING)
-WOMAN: Return to the hospital.

605
00:33:30,761 --> 00:33:32,761
-(GRUNTS)
-Sorry.

606
00:33:32,841 --> 00:33:34,201
Pressed for time.

607
00:33:34,281 --> 00:33:35,441
NARDOLE: That was good!

608
00:33:35,521 --> 00:33:36,721
Venusian Aikido.

609
00:33:36,801 --> 00:33:38,961
I thought you needed
four arms for Venusian.

610
00:33:39,041 --> 00:33:41,001
I've got hidden talents,
as well as hidden arms.

611
00:33:50,241 --> 00:33:51,241
(YAWNS)

612
00:34:03,921 --> 00:34:04,961
NARDOLE: But it's been 10 minutes,

613
00:34:05,041 --> 00:34:06,481
so, she must have been down there

614
00:34:06,561 --> 00:34:07,681
-for years.
-Yeah.

615
00:34:07,921 --> 00:34:10,921
NARDOLE: We could take the TARDIS,
go back, and get it right.

616
00:34:11,001 --> 00:34:13,601
This close to a black hole, we'll never
be able to pilot her accurately.

617
00:34:17,041 --> 00:34:18,561
BILL: Do you think
they're coming down here?

618
00:34:18,641 --> 00:34:20,641
Because if they are,
where does that lift arrive?

619
00:34:23,681 --> 00:34:24,761
Just asking.

620
00:34:29,201 --> 00:34:30,681
You are dear to me.

621
00:34:31,121 --> 00:34:34,121
You are my dearest person.

622
00:34:34,841 --> 00:34:36,241
-You are like...
-I know.

623
00:34:36,321 --> 00:34:37,481
A mother to me.

624
00:34:37,561 --> 00:34:39,241
Definitely not a mother.

625
00:34:40,641 --> 00:34:42,001
Or an aunt.

626
00:34:42,881 --> 00:34:43,881
No.

627
00:34:44,161 --> 00:34:46,681
But this question you must not ask.

628
00:34:48,361 --> 00:34:50,361
(EXHALES) Why not?

629
00:34:50,441 --> 00:34:53,201
Because if you do,
I think I might tell you.

630
00:34:55,321 --> 00:34:57,641
Aw, sorry, mate.

631
00:34:58,321 --> 00:35:00,801
-Guess what I'm about to do.
-Do not. Do not do this.

632
00:35:01,441 --> 00:35:02,601
I'm gonna ask you again.

633
00:35:03,761 --> 00:35:04,801
(SIGHS)

634
00:35:06,721 --> 00:35:08,121
When you hug me...

635
00:35:10,201 --> 00:35:11,761
It hurts my heart.

636
00:35:12,401 --> 00:35:13,401
Aw.

637
00:35:14,001 --> 00:35:15,001
Sweet.

638
00:35:15,441 --> 00:35:19,001
No, your chest unit, it digs right in.

639
00:35:41,281 --> 00:35:42,601
BILL: You sure about the mask?

640
00:35:42,681 --> 00:35:44,121
-MR RAZOR: Is burgling mask.
-Why?

641
00:35:44,201 --> 00:35:45,481
-Just in case.
-In case of what?

642
00:35:45,561 --> 00:35:46,641
Shh!

643
00:35:50,201 --> 00:35:51,521
BILL: But it's locked.

644
00:35:54,201 --> 00:35:57,041
-Where did you get that?
-I have burglary skills.

645
00:35:57,601 --> 00:35:59,841
They don't let just anyone
wear a mask like this, you know.

646
00:35:59,921 --> 00:36:02,081
It's got your name on the label.

647
00:36:03,401 --> 00:36:05,521
I also have key to operating theatre.

648
00:36:08,601 --> 00:36:10,001
I clean up on Wednesdays.

649
00:36:20,721 --> 00:36:21,721
(BILL GASPS)

650
00:36:22,481 --> 00:36:24,801
-(PANTING)
-It's all right, it's all right.

651
00:36:25,361 --> 00:36:28,401
It's just, you know, work in progress.

652
00:36:32,001 --> 00:36:34,441
So, these lifts, where do we find them?

653
00:36:36,121 --> 00:36:37,961
It's through there, somewhere.

654
00:36:38,041 --> 00:36:40,201
Oh! I like the hat.

655
00:36:42,041 --> 00:36:44,561
I'm going to ask for a hat
when it's my turn.

656
00:36:44,641 --> 00:36:45,681
BILL: Your turn?

657
00:36:45,761 --> 00:36:50,081
No, actually,
I'm afraid, Miss Potts, it's your turn.

658
00:36:50,521 --> 00:36:52,161
Thank you for bringing her, Mr Razor.

659
00:36:52,241 --> 00:36:54,961
Ah, you see through my clever disguise.

660
00:36:55,721 --> 00:36:56,801
Stupid thing.

661
00:36:56,881 --> 00:36:58,521
You... You didn't?

662
00:36:59,401 --> 00:37:00,961
Please, tell me you didn't.

663
00:37:01,041 --> 00:37:02,441
Is for your own good.

664
00:37:02,921 --> 00:37:04,201
Make you strong.

665
00:37:04,281 --> 00:37:05,721
Ready for the Exodus.

666
00:37:05,801 --> 00:37:07,441
I'm sorry about the deception.

667
00:37:07,521 --> 00:37:10,081
It's best to get people in here
without them knowing why.

668
00:37:10,161 --> 00:37:12,801
You don't want screaming
in the main part of the hospital.

669
00:37:12,881 --> 00:37:15,441
Don't you touch me!
Don't you lay a finger on me.

670
00:37:15,521 --> 00:37:18,281
This unit of yours won't last forever,
you know.

671
00:37:18,361 --> 00:37:19,881
You need the full upgrade.

672
00:37:19,961 --> 00:37:22,561
You're not gonna turn me
into one of those things.

673
00:37:22,641 --> 00:37:27,041
I'm rebuilding you, to survive
in a world not made for flesh.

674
00:37:27,121 --> 00:37:28,561
But, look at them.

675
00:37:28,641 --> 00:37:31,321
They're screaming in pain
every second they're alive!

676
00:37:31,961 --> 00:37:33,641
But, we've got something for that now.

677
00:37:33,721 --> 00:37:36,121
This won't stop you
feeling pain, but, uh...

678
00:37:38,241 --> 00:37:39,921
It will stop you caring about it.

679
00:37:41,401 --> 00:37:43,561
It fits over your head.

680
00:37:49,841 --> 00:37:52,161
Okay, you two,
welcome to a new time-zone.

681
00:37:53,161 --> 00:37:54,801
Not knowing the differential,

682
00:37:54,881 --> 00:37:56,721
I don't know how much time
has passed here.

683
00:37:57,441 --> 00:37:58,921
(CLOCK TICKING)

684
00:38:00,201 --> 00:38:02,121
Right, we have to find out
more about this ship.

685
00:38:02,201 --> 00:38:03,201
On it.

686
00:38:03,281 --> 00:38:06,641
No, Missy, you do it.
Nardole, you come with me.

687
00:38:07,721 --> 00:38:09,521
But, I'm the computer guy.
That's always me!

688
00:38:09,601 --> 00:38:10,881
Sorry, she's cleverer.

689
00:38:11,401 --> 00:38:13,281
-She's more evil.
-Same thing.

690
00:38:13,361 --> 00:38:14,961
-It really isn't.
-No, it is a little bit.

691
00:38:15,041 --> 00:38:16,281
Little bit the same.

692
00:38:16,361 --> 00:38:18,081
-Anyway...
-Yes, thank you.

693
00:38:18,161 --> 00:38:19,201
DOCTOR: Nardole!

694
00:38:30,041 --> 00:38:31,041
Hello.

695
00:38:34,281 --> 00:38:36,041
Hello, ordinary person.

696
00:38:36,121 --> 00:38:39,441
Please maintain
a minimum separation of three feet.

697
00:38:39,521 --> 00:38:41,361
I'm really trying
not to kill anyone today.

698
00:38:41,441 --> 00:38:42,921
It would be tremendously helpful

699
00:38:43,001 --> 00:38:46,521
if your major arteries
were out of reach.

700
00:38:46,601 --> 00:38:48,081
(LAUGHS)

701
00:38:49,401 --> 00:38:52,281
I have been so looking forward
to meeting you.

702
00:38:52,361 --> 00:38:53,641
Right, well...

703
00:38:53,721 --> 00:38:55,521
I'm very happy for you.

704
00:38:55,601 --> 00:38:58,121
MR RAZOR: I was watching you
on the screen.

705
00:38:58,201 --> 00:39:01,841
It took me a while
to work out who you were.

706
00:39:34,841 --> 00:39:35,841
(YELPS)

707
00:39:37,561 --> 00:39:38,561
(EXHALES)

708
00:39:39,121 --> 00:39:41,641
There's always a scary thing with you,
isn't there?

709
00:39:41,721 --> 00:39:43,241
You're only getting that now?

710
00:39:45,721 --> 00:39:49,201
Oh, this is super interesting.

711
00:39:49,281 --> 00:39:51,321
I assumed this ship was from Earth,

712
00:39:51,401 --> 00:39:53,961
full of squishable,
little humans, but...

713
00:39:54,041 --> 00:39:57,521
-It's not from Earth at all, is it?
-You don't remember me, do you?

714
00:39:57,601 --> 00:40:01,161
MISSY: Looks like an Earth-like planet,
but not Earth itself.

715
00:40:01,241 --> 00:40:04,201
Very Earth-like! If planets had twins...

716
00:40:04,281 --> 00:40:06,561
You don't remember being here before,
do you?

717
00:40:06,641 --> 00:40:07,801
I've never been here before.

718
00:40:07,881 --> 00:40:09,041
Will you please stop whittering on,

719
00:40:09,121 --> 00:40:11,241
or I'll have to splat your brains
for finger paint.

720
00:40:11,321 --> 00:40:15,801
Oh, you have been here before,
you really can trust me on that.

721
00:40:15,881 --> 00:40:17,681
(MUMBLING) Planet... Which planet...

722
00:40:18,961 --> 00:40:21,641
NARDOLE: Hmm,
there's a lot of genetics...

723
00:40:21,721 --> 00:40:23,121
Bio-engineering...

724
00:40:23,601 --> 00:40:25,841
There's a lot of stuff
about something called Exodus.

725
00:40:27,361 --> 00:40:29,001
Operation Exodus.

726
00:40:49,681 --> 00:40:51,121
(MACHINES BEEPING)

727
00:41:10,361 --> 00:41:12,721
Look at that. This ship is from Mondas.

728
00:41:16,681 --> 00:41:17,881
(ROBOTIC WHIRRING)

729
00:41:21,081 --> 00:41:22,241
It's a Cyberman!

730
00:41:23,161 --> 00:41:25,481
A Mondasian Cyberman!

731
00:41:27,441 --> 00:41:30,641
-Doctor!
-Doctor Who! Doctor, Doctor!

732
00:41:31,401 --> 00:41:32,841
(LAUGHING)

733
00:41:35,601 --> 00:41:36,641
Okay, listen to me.

734
00:41:37,361 --> 00:41:40,121
I may be about to take
that silly, little gun from you...

735
00:41:40,201 --> 00:41:43,281
He'll never forgive you, you know.
He'll never set you free.

736
00:41:44,321 --> 00:41:49,241
Not when he discovers
what you did to his little friend.

737
00:41:49,321 --> 00:41:51,801
I haven't done anything
to his silly, little friend.

738
00:41:51,881 --> 00:41:54,521
Oh, but I'm afraid you did.

739
00:41:56,921 --> 00:41:58,441
A long time ago.

740
00:42:01,121 --> 00:42:02,401
DOCTOR: You're brand new.

741
00:42:02,961 --> 00:42:05,121
Fresh out of the factory,
you're not ready for a fight yet.

742
00:42:05,601 --> 00:42:07,441
He does look a little bit ready.

743
00:42:07,841 --> 00:42:10,281
Bill Potts, do you know where she is?

744
00:42:10,761 --> 00:42:12,081
Where is Bill Potts?

745
00:42:12,161 --> 00:42:14,401
(IN ROBOTIC VOICE) Doctor.

746
00:42:15,641 --> 00:42:16,881
You know me?

747
00:42:16,961 --> 00:42:19,521
You are Doctor.

748
00:42:19,601 --> 00:42:21,721
Am I supposed to know
what you're talking about?

749
00:42:21,801 --> 00:42:23,401
Would it help you focus

750
00:42:23,481 --> 00:42:27,121
if I extracted some of your vital organs
and made a lovely soup?

751
00:42:27,201 --> 00:42:29,041
You would never be so...

752
00:42:29,841 --> 00:42:31,081
Self-destructive.

753
00:42:31,161 --> 00:42:32,161
So what?

754
00:42:32,241 --> 00:42:33,481
But then again...

755
00:42:35,121 --> 00:42:36,281
Neither would I.

756
00:42:37,801 --> 00:42:39,761
Listen, we mean you no harm.

757
00:42:40,521 --> 00:42:41,681
We're just passing through.

758
00:42:41,761 --> 00:42:43,441
We're looking for Bill Potts,
friend of mine.

759
00:42:43,521 --> 00:42:45,561
-Bill Potts?
-Yes!

760
00:42:45,641 --> 00:42:47,641
Bill Potts, you're a Cyberman.

761
00:42:47,721 --> 00:42:50,401
You're part of a neural net,
can you find her?

762
00:42:50,481 --> 00:42:53,321
I love disguises.

763
00:42:54,481 --> 00:42:56,241
Do you still like disguises?

764
00:42:57,041 --> 00:43:01,961
Of course, they are rather necessary
when you happen to be

765
00:43:02,041 --> 00:43:05,161
-someone's former prime minister.
-(GASPS)

766
00:43:09,361 --> 00:43:12,881
-Accessing Bill Potts.
-Get back from it.

767
00:43:13,481 --> 00:43:17,321
Locating Bill Potts.

768
00:43:19,561 --> 00:43:22,841
I am Bill Potts.

769
00:43:24,081 --> 00:43:25,241
Hello, Missy.

770
00:43:26,081 --> 00:43:27,561
I'm The Master.

771
00:43:29,001 --> 00:43:31,281
I'm very worried about my future.

772
00:43:33,241 --> 00:43:34,481
Give us a kiss.

773
00:43:35,321 --> 00:43:36,321
Bill?

774
00:43:37,361 --> 00:43:38,641
Bill, talk to me.

775
00:43:38,721 --> 00:43:40,041
DOCTOR: What've they done to you?

776
00:43:40,441 --> 00:43:41,761
Operation Exodus.

777
00:43:42,481 --> 00:43:43,561
NARDOLE: Whatever that is.

778
00:43:44,561 --> 00:43:47,081
MISSY: Oh, wrong name, for a start.

779
00:43:47,601 --> 00:43:49,401
I waited.

780
00:43:49,881 --> 00:43:52,081
MISSY: This is not an exodus, is it?

781
00:43:54,321 --> 00:43:55,881
More of a beginning, really.

782
00:43:55,961 --> 00:43:57,041
Isn't it?

783
00:43:57,121 --> 00:43:59,081
I waited.

784
00:43:59,161 --> 00:44:01,561
THE MASTER: In fact,
do you know what I'd call it?

785
00:44:06,681 --> 00:44:07,881
(GASPS)

786
00:44:08,641 --> 00:44:10,361
I'd call it a genesis.

787
00:44:11,921 --> 00:44:12,961
You've met the ex.

788
00:44:13,681 --> 00:44:17,881
Specifically, the genesis
of the Cybermen.

789
00:44:23,081 --> 00:44:27,681
I waited for you.

790
00:44:36,801 --> 00:44:38,801
(THEME MUSIC PLAYING)

791
00:45:04,641 --> 00:45:08,801
MISSY: The whole city is a machine
to turn people into Cybermen.

792
00:45:08,881 --> 00:45:11,081
What do you think?
It's exciting, isn't it?

793
00:45:11,561 --> 00:45:12,761
DOCTOR: You know the stories.

794
00:45:13,041 --> 00:45:16,401
There's only ever been one way
to stop that many Cybermen.

795
00:45:17,721 --> 00:45:18,721
Me!

796
00:45:19,761 --> 00:45:20,881
Stand with me.

